Intro

This document shows what changes about results if we look for main effects post-termination, rather than just looking at specific individual dates (either 1wk postkill, aka Postkill; or 4wk postkill, aka Midseason).

Hot water extractable carbohydrates

For HWC, the new figure on the right tells a different story from the old on the left.

But the two figures don't conflict since the new on the right highlights the NP effect over both dates, whereas the old/left with the differences only at midseason just shows the kill effect ignoring cover crop, which is important because NP highlights that CT has higher HWC than the no-till methods lower in the profile. On the right, the clover (not vetch) elevates HWC in the surface soil, only when it is tilled in, maybe because the shoots are contributing to HWC. Or, tillage increases HWC, but only if CC is present. Kinda six and one have dozen. In the deeper soil, tillage increased HWC relative to FM, but only in NP so this means I will need to have rewritten the paper a little because I currently (as of Feb 2021) say in the paper that HWC was higher because of cover crop residue. So its more of a soil disruption thing.

Soil moisture (gravimetric water content)

Next, there was a year X kill X date X depth interaction before.

Is there anything if we pay attention to the lower order year X kill X depth interaction (i.e. ignore the date effect)? No, according to the ANOVA. So ther's not a new figure to contrast this one with.

What is new about this postkill main effects ANOVA? Two things: cc X year and cc X kill X depth

First, cc X year is pointing out that HV has higher moisture postkill than NP both years, and clover in 2012. This could be of pracitical importance if someone wants a cover crop that will conserve more moisture during the growing saeson. Old, all-dates figure on the left; New, no prekill figure on the right.

So the figure on the right shows that HV in both years does the same thing elevating moisture compared to the NP. But HV=CC and NP=CC in 2013.

Second, there is a cc X kill X depth from the ANOVA. There's not a figure or table from before excluding pre-kill to compare this to since there wasn't any cc X kill interactions.

New

The closest thing to this is the year X date X cover figure (farther above on the left) that shows a cover effect, but only at certain times rather than in certain termination methods. Anyways this kind of contradicts the cc X year effect above so we should probably disregard the former.

With all the soil H2O stuff, it's only helpful in the paper if if backs up the other soil C & N and aggregation data, since this isn't really a study about soil water exactly.

So these cover crop effects on either of the two dates are apparent as main effects post termination over both of the dates as well. I think concentrating on the main effects post kill doesn't change our interpretation really, since for respiration there is still no signifiant difference, and for mineralizable N the overall post-termination effect is mainly coming from the 1wk postkill date.

Conclusions

  • For MBC, mineralizable N and minerlizable C, post kill main effects doesn't add anything or highlight anything that wasn't significant in the old analysis.
  • However, for HWC, at 0-5cm, clover has higher HWC than NP in the tilled plots, and tilled clover has higher HWC than non-tilled clover from 0-5 cm as well.
  • For soil moisture, we now notice that HV soil is wetter than NP in 2013, whereas this was not significant before (HV was already wetter in 2012).
  • However, soil moisture is higher in HV than CC or NP only in 0-5cm, non-tilled soil, and higher in HV only in mowed soil at 0-15cm.
  • For aggregate MWD, this new analysis wouldnt've made a difference since there I only ever measured MWD once after termination each year anyways.
